    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_title">Troubleshooting</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_health_title">Health check fails</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_health_1">Is the gateway process running?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_health_2">Is port 18789 open in your firewall?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_health_3">Is the gateway bound to 0.0.0.0 (not just localhost)?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_health_4">Check: openclaw gateway status</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_scan_title">No gateways found in scan</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_scan_1">Is your phone on the same Wi-Fi as the host?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_scan_2">Does your router allow mDNS / multicast?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_scan_3">Is client isolation disabled on the access point?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_firewall_title">Firewall blocking port 18789</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_firewall_windows">Windows (PowerShell as Admin): New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "OpenClaw Gateway" -Direction Inbound -Protocol TCP -LocalPort 18789 -Action Allow -Profile Private</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_firewall_macos">macOS: System Settings → Network → Firewall → Options → add openclaw, or run: sudo /usr/libexec/ApplicationFirewall/socketfilterfw --add $(which openclaw)</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_firewall_linux_ufw">Linux (UFW): sudo ufw allow 18789/tcp</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_firewall_linux_firewalld">Linux (firewalld): sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=18789/tcp &amp;&amp; sudo firewall-cmd --reload</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_firewall_test">Test from another machine: nc -zv [host-ip] 18789</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_auth_title">Auth error</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_auth_1">Does the token in openclaw.json match what you entered in GhostCrab?</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_auth_2">Try restarting the gateway after editing openclaw.json.</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_title">Host browser works, phone doesn\'t</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_1">Re-read the host IP carefully. A one-digit typo (192.168.0.23 vs 192.168.9.23) looks identical and will silently time out forever. Compare against ipconfig / ifconfig on the host.</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_2">The IP you enter here must be the host\'s LAN IP. Never 127.0.0.1, localhost, or 10.0.2.2 — those only resolve on the host itself.</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_3">Docker Desktop on Windows + WSL2 Mirrored networking is incompatible. If C:\\Users\\&lt;you&gt;\\.wslconfig contains networkingMode=Mirrored, loopback will work but LAN port forwarding silently breaks. Remove that line, run: wsl --shutdown, then restart Docker Desktop.</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_4">Windows firewall rule must match the active network profile. Check: Get-NetConnectionProfile. If it shows Public, -Profile Private alone will not match — use -Profile Any or widen the existing rule: Set-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "OpenClaw Gateway" -Profile Any.</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_5">Confirm LAN reachability from a second device on the same Wi-Fi: curl http://[host-ip]:18789/health. If that also fails, the phone is not the problem — router client-isolation, firewall, or gateway bind-address is.</string>
    <string name="onboarding_troubleshoot_host_vs_lan_6">If clearing the app fixed it, you had a stale saved profile with a typo. Re-enter the IP carefully and use Scan LAN when possible — auto-discovery avoids manual-typing bugs.</string>
</resources>
